<![CDATA[::taxonomy:Strains M and S were sequenced by Washington 
University School of Medicine Genome Sequencing Center (WUGSC) and the J. 
Craig Venter Institute (JCVI), respectively::endTaxonomy:"The Anopheles gambiae M and S genome sequencing projects used pools of 
DNA from colonies established in 2005 from Mali.  These colonies are available 
from the Malaria Research and Reference Reagent Resource Center (MR4;
www.mr4.org); neither was deliberately inbred. 
M form: Founding members of the A. gambiae Mali-NIH colony were collected 
indoors as blood fed adult females in Niono, Mali in June 2005.  Approximately 
80 isofemale families molecularly identified as A. gambiae M form were used to 
establish the colony, which was subsequently karyotyped as 2Rbc/bc; 2La/a. 
S form: Founding members of the A. gambiae Pimperena colony were collected 
indoors as blood fed adult females in Pimperena, Mali in November 2005.  
Approximately 5 isofemale families molecularly identified as A. gambiae S form 
were used to establish the colony, which was subsequently karyotyped as 2Rb/b; 
2La/+.  The exclusive presence of the uninverted (2L+
a
) arrangement in the S 
colony led to an increase in S private polymorphism sampled between the 
inversion breakpoints (figs. S1 and S4).
The Mali-NIH and Pimperena karyotypes would have been considered 
characteristic of chromosomal forms MOPTI and SAVANNA, respectively (S1).  
However, we avoid the chromosomal form Classification here, given lack of 
concordance between chromosomal and molecular (rDNA-based) definitions of 
population structure (S2).
For both genome projects, adult males were the source of DNA for plasmid 
libraries, while DNA from pupae of mixed sexes was used to prepare BAC 
libraries.  Fosmid libraries were constructed from pupae of mixed sexes for the S 
project, and from adult males for the M project.  
Sequencing and assembly
An. gambiae M and S form genomes were sequenced by the Washington 
University School of Medicine Genome Sequencing Center (WUGSC) and the J. 
Craig Venter Institute (JCVI), respectively.  DNA samples derived from whole 
mosquitoes were provided by the University of Notre Dame and MR4.  BAC
libraries were provided by the Clemson University Genomics Institute (CUGI), 
and are available through CUGI or MR4." (M. K. N. Lawniczak, et al. Widespread Divergence Between Incipient Anopheles gambiae Species Revealed by Whole Genome Sequences Science 330, 512 (2010).) mtDNA was sequenced by :
Beard CB et al., "The mitochondrial genome of the mosquito Anopheles gambiae: DNA sequence, genome organization, and comparisons with mitochondrial sequences of other insects.", Insect Mol Biol, 1993; 2 (2) :103-24. Publication not available online. There is also an updated nuclear genome sequence, but no information was provided regarding the specimens that were sequenced (Sharakhova MV et al., "Update of the Anopheles gambiae PEST genome assembly.", Genome Biol, 2007; 8 (1) :R5
)]]>
